BugPattern.ShortDescription: Format string should use %n rather than \n
BugPattern.Details: This format string includes a newline character (\n). In format strings, it is generally preferable to use %n, which will produce the platform-specific line separator.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Class names shouldn't shadow simple name of implemented interface
BugPattern.Details: This class/interface has a simple name that is identical to that of an implemented/extended interface, except that the interface is in a different package (e.g., alpha.Foo extends beta.Foo). This can be exceptionally confusing, create lots of situations in which you have to look at import statements to resolve references and creates many opportunities to accidentally define methods that do not override methods in their superclasses.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Method invokes inefficient floating-point Number constructor; use static valueOf instead
BugPattern.Details:
Using new Double(double) is guaranteed to always result in a new object whereas Double.valueOf(double) allows caching of values to be done by the compiler, class library, or JVM. Using of cached values avoids object allocation and the code will be faster.

Unless the class must be compatible with JVMs predating Java 1.5, use either autoboxing or the valueOf() method when creating instances of Double and Float.

This method contains a double assignment of a field; e.g. 

int x,y;
public void foo() {
    x = x = 17;
}

Assigning to a field twice is useless, and may indicate a logic error or typo.
